Let’s start seeing real life... 
•••
I love the original by @theweeknd so much, I was inspired to create a version about social media/phone addiction. It’s something I really struggle with, especially having a job that is so deeply intertwined with digital lust. A little reminder to see real life. 

It pained me to reframe this project for IG because the full frame video is such a visual treat. Link in bio to watch it, in all its glory on YouTube. Shoutouts to my DP @cldorson who nailed my vision and brought such cinematic brilliance to the project. 

Shoutouts to @durranibros for the incredible recreation of the song. Usually it’s mentally straining to listen to a song 100 times while shooting but this one was a treat. 

Thank you to the entire crew for working hard on this beast of a concept that took three shoot days, one of which was overnight. Shoutouts @friedpotayters for always reassuring everyone that “Lilly’s insanely ambitious ideas are somehow possible,” because we always find a way. 

I’m really proud of this one. In some ways, it communicates something I can’t with just words. Turning pain into art. I hope you enjoy it ❤️

#BlindingLikes

Based 100% on a true story 😂💀 real talk, we’ve made a lot of progress in this industry in terms of diversity but there’s still a long way to go because the same group of powerful people run the show behind the scenes. This sketch is dedicated to anyone who has ever been in a room, pitching an idea about their experience, only to have no one else understand it. (Me. This video is dedicated to me.) Here’s to more diversity on the screen but also behind the camera and in the business. 

Also, I wanna say that these other actors became my homies in like four seconds. I legit had a blast with them and also kind of... turned into them? LOL. A hoot. #LateWithLilly

node.text:
It’s not party time. P-A-R-T-WHY? Because there’s still COVID. 😫

Obviously trying to parody any part of Jim Carrey is a dream for me. Plz someone holla at me when they do the female remake👀 but jokes aside, I know lockdown and quarantine have been tough. It feels never ending. But I also know many places around the world, including my hometown of Toronto and my motherland of India are experiencing a wave of cases. I know we all want this to be over but the reality is that it’s not. We still need to wear masks and understand this pandemic is impacting people immensely. So if your biggest issue is having to wear an annoying mask rn, recognize your privilege and just wear the damn mask. And if you feel like your rights are being taken away because you have to wear a mask, there’s plenty of other examples of peoples rights being disregarded that you can be angry about. Perhaps dedicate your energy there. Thank you! Love ❤️ #LateWithLilly

This has been on my mind for a while now and today I woke up feeling inspired to deliver this message with love and light. Like many of you, I am passionate about representation and breaking those glass ceilings. For most of my career I have truly tried to see a picture bigger than myself. Sure, sometimes I get lost and stumble but in the end, I always know the bigger goal is to ensure I’m not the last to do what I’m doing. That’s the real legacy. 

But it’s not enough to say we want representation. We must show we support it and we must demand it. This interview with @reneemontgomery really captures the experience of a lot of minorities. If you want more female athletes with resources, you need to watch the games, buy tickets and be loud with your support. If you want more representation in media, you need to actually watch the shows, post about them and follow the accounts. I’m all for fighting the good fight but I feel we often ignore the business behind representation. Make diversity undeniably beneficial and you will see more diversity.

And on a personal note, every time a new Indian show comes out, I’m heartbroken to see our own community so divided and quick to criticize. “That’s not Indian enough,” “That’s too Indian,” “That’s not my experience.” With love, that attitude towards our own does nothing to serve the greater good. Real representation means we can have a range of stories from serious to childish, from epic to foolish, from educational to reality tv. So let us realize that our own division is what often stands in our own way. Hating on Indian shows is not going to get us more Indian shows. Across the board, when I chat with my friends in the industry, their own communities are the biggest supporters and biggest criticizers. We need to think on that. 

This isn’t even about my show or my career. This isn’t about me. This applies to any person, tv show, movie, musician, entrepreneur, scientist, etc that needs our support. 

Real talk, we need to understand that those who do not want to see us thrive work very hard, so we must work harder. It’s time to show up. Drop a ❤️ if you’re down x 

Love y’all ❤️

IM BACK BABY! New sketches every Thursday starting next week. Link in bio to subscribe on YouTube! ❤️

For the past little bit I haven’t made digital content because I’ve been meditating, eating right, drinking water, being active and HUSTLING. Between @unicornislandprod projects and @dollfaceonhulu I’ve been putting in WERK. But I love connecting with my online community so much and I missed it! So I carved out time and made some content. Because throughout everything I’m doing in my career, my channel is still a place for my unfiltered ideas and somewhere I can make what I think is funny and important. What a privilege! Thanks for riding with me ❤️

Tag your Akka, Abuela, Paaji and best friend because ya girl is back. Lets have some fun!

node.text: Shout outs to Brown girls everywhere. Love all folk but this one is for the girls who rock them lenghas, suits and sarees. Who deal with earrings that stab their necks and dupattas/chunnies that are too heavy and prickly. This one is for the girls who need 6 arms to hold their saree because they need to pee. For the girls who keep trying to get their bindi centred. For the girls who squeeze those bangles on even though it hurts. For the girls who tie that salwar extra tight because they want to dance. For the women who get mendhi done and sacrifice their hands for 5 hours. I see you. I love you. I’m proud of you. What I do is for you. If you’re a Brown girl and you know you’re hot, comment with a 🙏🏽🙏🏽🙏🏽🙏🏽!!!
